Replicating my comment on bug#11624 comment#112:
"Hi, I start experimenting with N20070105-0010 and dragging on java editor and I found some issues, e.g. on the following snippet:
public class Teste {
}
Select the "class Teste" string and drag it into some part of the same string. There are some weird results depending on where you drop it, e.g. if you drop it between "c" and "l" from "class", you get "elass Teste".
Another weird thing is the undo support: on the above example, I have to hit Ctrl+Z 2 times to restore the initial text. Hitting Ctrl+Z just one time gives me the text on some kind of "intermediate" state: "public cclass Testelass Teste {"."

I believe Steve is suggesting that you use getData() and setData() on the StyledText widget and not on the DragSource or DropTarget. For example, if you want to pass the sommething (eg. DragSource or anything else) to the DropTarget you would write something like this:

	public void dragStart(DragSourceEvent e) {
		((DragSource) e.widget).getControl().setData("DRAG_START_DATA", e.widget);
	}

Similarly, if you want to return something (eg. DropTarget) from the drop to the DragSource you would do this:

	public void drop(DropTargetEvent event) {
		((DropTarget) e.widget).getControl().setData("DROP_DATA", e.widget);
	}

Just be sure to clear these data when you're done with the drag-n-drop:

	public void dragFinished(DragSourceEvent e) {
		((DropTarget) e.widget).getControl().setData("DROP_DATA", null);
		((DragSource) e.widget).getControl().setData("DRAG_START_DATA", null);
	}

On the drop target side, if the DRAG_START_DATA is not null then you know that the drag-n-drop operation is on the same widget (eg. StyledText). On the drag source side, if the DROP_DATA is not null then the drop was on the same widget as the drag source. If the data is null, then the drag-n-drop is happening on different widgets (or applications).

To determine whether the editors are editing the same document, you may need to pass the "data" (eg. IEditorInput) through other ways (more global) that both editors can see. So, instead of storing the data using setData() of the widget you may need to assign it to a static field where both editor instances can get access to the data.

I wrote a little StyledTextDnD example to demonstrate the first problem. If you drag some text in the same editor then the default operation is a MOVE. But if you drag it to another instance of the editor then the default operation is a COPY. That's how Word and WordPad behave. If you want the example, please let me know and I'll send it to you.

